/* PasstheEPPP — Question Bank Batch 14
   Enhanced rationale format — 80 new questions across all 8 domains */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch14 = [
        // ===== Domain 1: Biological Bases (10) =====
        {domainId:1, q:"The default mode network (DMN) is most active during:", options:["Intense sustained concentration on externally focused cognitively demanding task performance","Mind-wandering, daydreaming, and self-referential thought during wakeful rest periods","Exclusively during REM sleep stages and never during any period of conscious wakefulness","Vigorous physical exercise engaging motor cortex and sensorimotor processing networks"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) The DMN (medial prefrontal cortex, posterior cingulate, precuneus) activates during rest, daydreaming, self-reflection, and internal mentation. It deactivates during focused external tasks. Abnormal DMN activity is linked to depression, ADHD, and Alzheimer's.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Intense concentration DEACTIVATES the DMN — task-positive networks take over.\n(C) The DMN is active during wakefulness, not exclusively during REM sleep.\n(D) Physical exercise engages motor and sensorimotor networks, not primarily the DMN."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Epigenetics in psychology refers to:", options:["Permanent changes in the DNA nucleotide sequence caused by spontaneous or induced mutations","Changes in gene expression caused by environmental factors without altering the DNA sequence","The exclusive study of monozygotic identical twins reared apart in behavioral genetics research","Commercially available genetic testing kits used to screen for heritable mental disorder risk"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Epigenetics studies how environmental factors (stress, diet, trauma) modify gene expression through mechanisms like DNA methylation and histone modification WITHOUT changing the actual DNA sequence. These changes can be heritable.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) DNA sequence mutations = genetic changes, not epigenetic modifications.\n(C) Twin studies are ONE method to study gene-environment interactions, not the definition.\n(D) Genetic testing identifies DNA variants — epigenetics is about expression regulation."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The locus coeruleus is the primary source of:", options:["Dopamine produced primarily by the ventral tegmental area and the substantia nigra","Serotonin produced primarily by the raphe nuclei located throughout the brainstem","Norepinephrine modulating arousal, attention, stress responses, and fight-or-flight reactions","Acetylcholine produced primarily by the basal forebrain nucleus basalis of Meynert"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (C) The locus coeruleus (brainstem, pons) is the principal norepinephrine-producing nucleus. It modulates arousal, attention, stress responses, and the fight-or-flight reaction. Dysregulation is implicated in PTSD, anxiety, and ADHD.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Dopamine → primarily from VTA and substantia nigra.\n(B) Serotonin → primarily from raphe nuclei in the brainstem.\n(D) Acetylcholine → primarily from basal forebrain and brainstem nuclei."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Glutamate is the brain's primary:", options:["Inhibitory neurotransmitter responsible for reducing neuronal excitability throughout the central nervous system","Excitatory neurotransmitter involved in learning, memory, synaptic plasticity, and long-term potentiation","Neuromodulator that diffusely projects throughout cortical networks to regulate mood and motivation","Endocrine hormone released into the bloodstream by pituitary and adrenal gland secretory cells"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Glutamate is the most abundant excitatory neurotransmitter in the CNS, involved in learning (LTP), memory, and synaptic plasticity. Excess glutamate causes excitotoxicity — implicated in stroke, TBI, and neurodegenerative diseases.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Primary inhibitory neurotransmitter = GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid).\n(C) Neuromodulators (dopamine, serotonin) modulate neurotransmission but aren't the primary excitatory signal.\n(D) Hormones are released into the bloodstream by endocrine glands — glutamate acts at synapses."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Neuroplasticity is GREATEST during:", options:["Late adulthood when compensatory neural mechanisms are most actively recruited and developed","Early childhood critical and sensitive periods when synaptic density peaks and pruning begins","Middle age exclusively when myelination of prefrontal cortical circuits reaches full completion","It remains perfectly constant and unchanging throughout the entire human lifespan without variation"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Neuroplasticity — the brain's ability to reorganize by forming new neural connections — is highest during critical/sensitive periods in early childhood. It decreases with age but never disappears entirely.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Late adulthood shows the LEAST neuroplasticity, though it still exists.\n(C) Middle age retains some plasticity but significantly less than childhood.\n(D) Plasticity DECREASES with age — it is NOT constant throughout life."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The ventral tegmental area (VTA) is a key structure in:", options:["Primary visual processing occurring in the occipital lobe striate and extrastriate cortical areas","The brain's reward and motivation circuitry projecting dopaminergic pathways to nucleus accumbens","Primary auditory processing occurring in temporal lobe Heschl's gyrus and surrounding cortex","Cerebellar motor coordination and procedural learning involving Purkinje cell circuit computations"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) The VTA is the origin of the mesolimbic dopamine pathway (VTA → nucleus accumbens), central to reward, motivation, reinforcement learning, and addiction. Also projects to the prefrontal cortex (mesocortical pathway).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Visual processing → occipital lobe (primary visual cortex, V1-V5).\n(C) Auditory processing → temporal lobe (primary auditory cortex, Heschl's gyrus).\n(D) Motor coordination → cerebellum and basal ganglia."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Kindling in epilepsy refers to:", options:["A single isolated seizure event without any progressive sensitization or threshold changes","Repeated subthreshold stimulations that eventually produce full seizures through progressive sensitization","Neurosurgical resection and removal of an identified epileptogenic seizure focus in cortical tissue","Iatrogenic medication-induced seizures caused by pharmacological side effects of prescribed treatments"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Kindling: repeated exposure to a subthreshold electrical/chemical stimulus eventually produces increasingly severe seizure responses. The brain becomes progressively more sensitive — a model for how seizure disorders develop and worsen.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) A single seizure event doesn't explain the progressive sensitization mechanism.\n(C) Surgical removal = surgical treatment for epilepsy (resection), not the kindling mechanism.\n(D) Medication-induced seizures are iatrogenic effects, not the kindling process."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The insula cortex is involved in:", options:["Only primary motor control of voluntary skeletal movements through corticospinal tract projections","Interoception, emotional awareness, empathy, disgust perception, and pain processing functions","Only primary visual processing of spatial orientation and object recognition in the visual field","Only expressive language production through coordination of articulatory motor speech programs"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) The insula processes interoceptive signals (internal body states), subjective emotional experience, empathy, disgust, pain, and risk assessment. It bridges bodily sensations with emotional awareness.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Motor control primarily involves the motor cortex, basal ganglia, and cerebellum.\n(C) Visual processing → occipital cortex.\n(D) Language production → Broca's area (left frontal lobe)."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Broca's area is located in the:", options:["Right temporal lobe processing music perception and prosodic speech contour recognition","Left inferior frontal gyrus controlling speech production, grammar, and language output","Occipital lobe processing primary visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus","Cerebellum coordinating motor timing, procedural learning, and postural balance control"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Broca's area (Brodmann areas 44/45) is in the left inferior frontal gyrus. It controls speech production, grammar, and language output. Damage produces non-fluent (expressive) aphasia.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Right temporal lobe → involved in music processing and non-verbal abilities.\n(C) Occipital lobe → visual processing.\n(D) Cerebellum → motor coordination, balance, and procedural learning."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Tardive dyskinesia is MOST associated with long-term use of:", options:["Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors prescribed for depressive and anxiety spectrum disorders","Benzodiazepine anxiolytic medications that enhance GABAergic inhibitory neurotransmission systemically","Typical first-generation antipsychotics that block dopamine D2 receptors causing receptor supersensitivity","Psychostimulant medications that increase catecholamine availability in prefrontal synaptic clefts"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (C) Tardive dyskinesia (TD) — involuntary, repetitive orofacial movements — develops after prolonged use of dopamine D2 receptor-blocking agents, especially typical antipsychotics (haloperidol, chlorpromazine). Due to dopamine receptor supersensitivity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) SSRIs don't block dopamine receptors and rarely cause movement disorders.\n(B) Benzodiazepines enhance GABA — they don't cause TD.\n(D) Stimulants increase dopamine rather than blocking it — they cause different side effects."},

        // ===== Domain 2: Cognitive-Affective (10) =====
        {domainId:2, q:"The testing effect (retrieval practice) demonstrates that:", options:["Simply studying more material through passive re-reading always proportionally improves memory retention","Actively retrieving information from memory strengthens retention more effectively than re-reading","Multiple-choice test formats are inherently superior to essay test formats for all learning","Testing invariably causes debilitating anxiety that significantly impairs all subsequent learning"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) The testing effect: actively retrieving information (practice testing) produces stronger, more durable learning than passive re-study (re-reading, highlighting). Effortful retrieval strengthens memory traces.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Passive re-studying shows diminishing returns — retrieval practice is more effective.\n(C) Both test formats can produce the testing effect; format superiority isn't the finding.\n(D) While test anxiety exists, the testing effect shows that retrieval practice ENHANCES learning overall."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Cognitive load theory distinguishes between:", options:["Only short-term and long-term memory storage systems within the modal memory architecture model","Intrinsic load (task complexity), extraneous load (poor design), and germane load (schema building)","Only explicit declarative memory and implicit nondeclarative memory taxonomic classification systems","Only sensory registration processing and subsequent motor output execution response pathways"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Sweller's cognitive load theory: intrinsic load (inherent task complexity), extraneous load (poor instructional design), and germane load (effort devoted to schema construction). Effective instruction minimizes extraneous load.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) STM/LTM distinction is part of Atkinson-Shiffrin's model, not cognitive load theory specifically.\n(C) Explicit/implicit memory is Squire's taxonomy, not related to cognitive load.\n(D) Sensory/motor processing relates to perception and action, not instructional load management."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The misinformation effect (Loftus) shows that:", options:["Human memory is always perfectly accurate and resistant to any form of external contamination","Post-event misleading information can substantially alter memories of the original experienced event","Only young children are susceptible to memory distortion from suggestive interviewing techniques","Memories are permanently fixed once initially encoded and can never be subsequently modified"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Loftus demonstrated that exposure to misleading information AFTER an event (leading questions, suggestive interviews) can contaminate, distort, or create false memories of the original event.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The misinformation effect specifically demonstrates memory INACCURACY and malleability.\n(C) Adults are also susceptible — though children and older adults may be more vulnerable.\n(D) Memories are highly reconstructive and can be modified by post-event information."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Amygdala hijack (Goleman) refers to:", options:["A neurosurgical procedure for removing the amygdala to treat refractory seizure disorders","An immediate emotional response that bypasses rational cortical processing through subcortical pathways","A hippocampal-dependent memory encoding process for consolidating emotional episodic events","A type of acquired traumatic brain injury resulting from focal damage to medial temporal structures"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Goleman popularized this term: the amygdala can trigger rapid emotional responses (especially fear/anger) via the thalamo-amygdala pathway BEFORE cortical areas fully process the information, producing impulsive emotional reactions.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's a neuropsychological concept, not a surgical procedure.\n(C) Memory encoding involves hippocampal processes — amygdala hijack is about immediate emotional reactivity.\n(D) It describes normal brain functioning under emotional stress, not pathological brain injury."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Prospective memory involves:", options:["Remembering past autobiographical events and episodic experiences from one's personal history","Remembering to perform intended actions in the future at an appropriate time or situation","Remembering general semantic facts and encyclopedic conceptual knowledge about the world","Remembering well-practiced procedural motor skills through implicit nondeclarative memory systems"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Prospective memory = remembering to DO something in the future (take medication at 3pm, pick up groceries). Distinct from retrospective memory (remembering past events or information).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Remembering past events = retrospective/episodic memory.\n(C) Remembering facts and concepts = semantic memory.\n(D) Remembering motor skills = procedural memory."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The peak-end rule (Kahneman) states that people evaluate experiences based on:", options:["The total cumulative duration of the experience weighted equally across all temporal moments","The most intense moment (peak) and the ending, largely ignoring the overall duration","Only the initial beginning moments of the experience with complete neglect of everything after","A perfectly accurate mathematical average calculated from all moments experienced throughout"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) People judge experiences by the peak intensity and the ending, largely ignoring duration. This explains why a painful procedure feels less bad if pain decreases near the end (even if total pain is greater).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Duration neglect — people don't weight total duration appropriately.\n(C) Beginnings matter less than peaks and endings in retrospective evaluation.\n(D) Retrospective evaluation is NOT an accurate average — it's biased toward peaks and endings."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Cognitive dissonance theory (Festinger) predicts that people who receive MINIMAL justification for counter-attitudinal behavior will:", options:["Maintain their original attitudes without any measurable change in beliefs or cognitive orientation","Show the MOST attitude change because insufficient external justification drives internal attribution","Show substantially less attitude change compared to those who received large external justification","Become increasingly more committed to strengthening and defending their original pre-existing attitude"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Insufficient justification effect: when external justification is minimal, people must internally justify their behavior by changing their attitudes. More justification = less dissonance = less attitude change.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Dissonance produces attitude change — people don't simply maintain conflicting cognitions.\n(C) LARGE justification reduces dissonance externally, producing LESS attitude change (the opposite).\n(D) Counter-attitudinal behavior with insufficient justification weakens the original attitude."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Source monitoring errors occur when:", options:["People permanently forget information entirely without any residual memory trace remaining","People remember information accurately but misattribute its original source or contextual origin","People possess flawless perfect memory with complete accuracy for both content and source","People deliberately and consciously fabricate false information with intentional deceptive motivation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Source monitoring errors: correctly remembering information but incorrectly attributing WHERE it came from (confusing a dream with reality, misremembering who told you something, or believing an imagined event actually happened).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Complete forgetting = different from source confusion — the information IS remembered, just misattributed.\n(C) Perfect memory doesn't involve attribution errors.\n(D) Source monitoring errors are UNINTENTIONAL memory failures, not deliberate deception."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The negativity bias refers to:", options:["A personality trait of chronic pessimism characterized by always thinking negatively about everything","The tendency for negative information to have greater psychological impact than equivalent positive information","A specific clinical diagnostic symptom exclusively associated with major depressive disorder presentations","A cognitive distortion identified within cognitive behavioral therapy such as catastrophizing or filtering"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Negativity bias: negative events, information, and emotions are processed more deeply, remembered better, and weighted more heavily in decision-making than equivalent positive information. This is an evolved adaptive mechanism.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's not a personality trait of pessimism — it's a universal cognitive tendency.\n(C) While depression amplifies negativity, the negativity bias is a normal phenomenon present in everyone.\n(D) CBT identifies cognitive distortions — the negativity bias is a broader cognitive science finding."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Working memory capacity is approximately:", options:["Essentially unlimited in storage capacity with no meaningful constraints on information maintenance","Approximately 4±1 chunks of information according to Cowan's updated capacity estimate research","At least 50 discrete items maintained simultaneously within the working memory buffer system","Only a single item at a time with absolutely no capacity for maintaining multiple representations"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Cowan's updated estimate: working memory holds approximately 4±1 chunks (revising Miller's classic 7±2). Chunking and rehearsal strategies can effectively increase functional capacity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Working memory is severely capacity-limited — that's its defining feature.\n(C) 50 items far exceeds working memory capacity.\n(D) While attention may focus on 1 item, working memory can maintain ~4 items simultaneously."},

        // ===== Domain 3: Social & Cultural (10) =====
        {domainId:3, q:"Bystander apathy (bystander effect) is MOST influenced by:", options:["The objective physical severity of the emergency situation witnessed by the observing bystanders","Diffusion of responsibility among witnesses and pluralistic ignorance about the situation's urgency","The biological sex or gender presentation of the victim requiring emergency assistance in public","The specific geographic time of day when the emergency event occurs in the bystanders' vicinity"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Darley & Latané: bystanders are less likely to help as group size increases due to diffusion of responsibility (someone else will help) and pluralistic ignorance (everyone looks calm, so it must not be serious).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Even severe emergencies show bystander effects — severity alone doesn't override the social dynamics.\n(C) Victim gender may play a minor role but isn't the primary mechanism driving the bystander effect.\n(D) Time of day can affect presence of bystanders but isn't the psychological mechanism."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Groupthink (Janis) is characterized by:", options:["Careful systematic consideration of all available alternative solutions before reaching final decisions","Pressure for unanimity that suppresses critical thinking, dissent, and independent evaluation","Productive constructive conflict and vigorous debate among all group members about decisions","Independent individual decision-making processes without any group conformity or social influence"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Janis's groupthink: cohesive groups under stress suppress dissent, create illusion of unanimity, self-censor, and use mindguards — producing defective decision-making (e.g., Bay of Pigs, Challenger disaster).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Careful consideration of alternatives is the OPPOSITE of groupthink — groupthink suppresses this.\n(C) Productive conflict is suppressed in groupthink — dissent is discouraged.\n(D) Groupthink is specifically a GROUP phenomenon, not individual decision-making."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The fundamental attribution error is the tendency to:", options:["Attribute other people's behavior primarily to situational and environmental contextual factors","Overattribute others' behavior to dispositional factors while underestimating situational influences","Always blame oneself for all negative outcomes regardless of external contributing circumstances","Make perfectly accurate and unbiased causal inferences about the determinants of behavior"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) FAE (correspondence bias): when explaining OTHERS' behavior, people overweight personality/character and underweight situational constraints. Less common in collectivist cultures.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Attributing to situational factors = the OPPOSITE tendency (actor-observer bias).\n(C) Always blaming oneself = depressive attributional style, not the FAE.\n(D) The FAE is specifically an attribution ERROR — it produces systematic inaccuracy."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Social facilitation theory predicts that the presence of others will:", options:["Always universally improve performance on every type of task regardless of task complexity","Improve performance on simple/well-learned tasks but impair performance on complex/novel tasks","Always universally impair performance across every type of task regardless of task familiarity","Have absolutely no measurable effect on task performance under any experimental conditions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Zajonc's drive theory: others' presence increases arousal, which enhances dominant responses. For well-learned tasks (dominant response = correct), performance improves. For novel/complex tasks (dominant response = errors), performance worsens.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Others' presence IMPAIRS performance on complex/unfamiliar tasks.\n(C) Others' presence IMPROVES performance on simple/well-practiced tasks.\n(D) The presence of others reliably affects performance — it doesn't have 'no effect'."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Relative deprivation theory explains that dissatisfaction arises when:", options:["People objectively possess very poor conditions measured by absolute economic poverty indicators","People perceive they have less than their comparison group, regardless of absolute material standing","People are genetically and temperamentally predisposed to chronic unhappiness and life dissatisfaction","People experience only physical material deprivation of basic survival needs like food and shelter"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Relative deprivation: dissatisfaction results from perceived discrepancy between what one has and what one's reference group has. Explains why economic growth doesn't always increase happiness, and why inequality fuels social unrest.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Objective conditions matter less than PERCEIVED discrepancy with reference groups.\n(C) Genetic predisposition relates to set-point theory, not relative deprivation.\n(D) Physical deprivation is absolute deprivation — relative deprivation is about social comparison."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Stereotype threat affects performance by:", options:["Increasing intrinsic motivation and enhancing task engagement through heightened arousal activation","Consuming working memory resources through anxiety, rumination, and excessive self-monitoring processes","Improving test-taking skills through increased vigilance and enhanced strategic cognitive processing","Having no demonstrable measurable effect on cognitive performance in any well-controlled study"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Stereotype threat impairs performance through multiple mechanisms: increased anxiety, rumination, self-monitoring, and working memory depletion — all of which divert cognitive resources from the task.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Stereotype threat typically DECREASES effective motivation by creating debilitating anxiety.\n(C) It IMPAIRS test performance, not improves test-taking skills.\n(D) Meta-analyses confirm significant, measurable effects on performance across many studies."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Milgram's obedience studies found that approximately what percentage of participants administered the maximum shock?", options:["Approximately 10% of participants administered the maximum voltage in the baseline condition","Approximately 35% of participants administered the maximum voltage in the baseline condition","Approximately 65% of participants administered the maximum voltage in the baseline condition","Approximately 95% of participants administered the maximum voltage in the baseline condition"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (C) In Milgram's baseline condition, approximately 65% of participants administered the maximum 450-volt shock when instructed by the authority figure — far exceeding initial predictions by psychiatrists (~1%).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) 10% dramatically underestimates — this was the expert prediction, not the actual result.\n(B) 35% underestimates the actual compliance rate.\n(D) 95% overestimates — about 35% DID refuse at some point."},
        {domainId:3, q:"In-group bias (in-group favoritism) occurs even in:", options:["Only real-world political and economic intergroup conflict situations involving scarce resource competition","Only between established racial and ethnic groups with long historical intergroup contact histories","Minimal group paradigm conditions based on entirely arbitrary and meaningless categorization criteria","Only structured therapeutic group settings supervised by a trained mental health professional"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (C) Tajfel's minimal group paradigm: even when groups are formed on trivial/random criteria (e.g., coin flip, art preference), members favor their in-group — demonstrating that mere categorization is sufficient for bias.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) In-group bias occurs even without any conflict or competition.\n(B) In-group bias extends far beyond ethnic groups — any social categorization can trigger it.\n(D) In-group bias is a general social phenomenon, not limited to therapy contexts."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The elaboration likelihood model (Petty & Cacioppo) distinguishes between:", options:["Conscious explicit attitudes and unconscious implicit attitudes measured by different assessment tools","Central (systematic argument processing) and peripheral (heuristic cue-based) persuasion routes","Only positive favorable attitudes and negative unfavorable attitudes toward persuasion targets","Intrinsic autonomous motivation and extrinsic controlled motivation as described by self-determination"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) ELM: central route = careful evaluation of message arguments (when motivated and able), producing durable attitude change. Peripheral route = reliance on cues (attractiveness, expertise) with less lasting change.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Conscious/unconscious attitudes relate to explicit/implicit attitude research, not ELM.\n(C) The ELM addresses HOW attitudes change (processing route), not attitude valence.\n(D) Intrinsic/extrinsic motivation = self-determination theory (Deci & Ryan), not ELM."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Scapegoat theory proposes that prejudice increases when:", options:["People are highly well-educated and possess sophisticated critical thinking analytical abilities","Frustrated individuals displace aggression onto vulnerable outgroups who serve as convenient targets","Economic conditions substantially improve and material prosperity increases for all population groups","People possess high self-esteem and strong positive self-concept reducing social comparison needs"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Scapegoat theory (based on frustration-aggression hypothesis): when people experience frustration (economic hardship, stress), they displace aggression onto vulnerable, less powerful groups who become scapegoats.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Education can REDUCE prejudice, not increase it.\n(C) Improving economic conditions would REDUCE frustration and scapegoating.\n(D) Low self-esteem (not high) is associated with greater need for outgroup derogation."},

        // ===== Domain 4: Growth & Lifespan (10) =====
        {domainId:4, q:"Teratogenic effects are MOST severe during:", options:["The germinal period spanning weeks 1-2 when the zygote undergoes initial cellular divisions","The embryonic period spanning weeks 3-8 when major organ systems undergo active organogenesis","The fetal period spanning months 3-9 when organ systems continue growth and functional maturation","After birth during the immediate neonatal period when the newborn adapts to extrauterine life"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) The embryonic period (weeks 3-8) is most vulnerable to teratogens because major organ systems are forming (organogenesis). Exposure during this period causes structural birth defects.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Germinal period (weeks 1-2): teratogen exposure typically causes all-or-nothing effects.\n(C) Fetal period: organs are already formed; teratogens cause functional rather than structural deficits.\n(D) After birth, the infant is no longer exposed to prenatal teratogens."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Scaffolding in Vygotsky's theory refers to:", options:["Peer-only learning without any involvement from adults or more knowledgeable individuals","Temporary support from a more knowledgeable other that is gradually removed as competence grows","Innate predetermined learning abilities that unfold through biological maturational processes alone","Punishment-based instructional approaches that suppress incorrect responses through aversive consequences"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Scaffolding (Wood, Bruner, & Ross, building on Vygotsky): the MKO provides just enough support within the ZPD, gradually withdrawing it ('fading') as the child masters the skill independently.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Scaffolding involves a MORE KNOWLEDGEABLE other, not peer-only learning.\n(C) Vygotsky emphasized SOCIAL learning, not innate abilities.\n(D) Scaffolding is supportive and collaborative, not punishment-based."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Gilligan's critique of Kohlberg argued that:", options:["Women are fundamentally morally inferior to men across all stages of moral development","Kohlberg's model was biased toward justice orientation and neglected care orientation reasoning","Moral development simply doesn't exist as a meaningful psychological construct or process","Young children are completely incapable of engaging in any form of moral reasoning whatsoever"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Gilligan (In a Different Voice, 1982): Kohlberg's stages prioritized abstract justice principles (more common in male socialization) over care/relationship orientation (more common in female socialization), creating systematic bias.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Gilligan argued the opposite — women use a DIFFERENT but equally valid moral framework.\n(C) Gilligan affirmed moral development exists but argued it takes different forms.\n(D) This wasn't about children's capacity — it was about gender bias in the model."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Resilience in child development is BEST predicted by:", options:["The complete absence of all adversity, stress, and challenging life circumstances throughout childhood","At least one stable, supportive relationship with a caring and consistently responsive adult","High socioeconomic status alone without consideration of interpersonal relationship quality factors","Exclusively genetic temperamental factors without any environmental or relational protective contributions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Research consistently identifies a stable, nurturing relationship with at least one adult (parent, grandparent, teacher, mentor) as the single most important factor promoting resilience in adverse circumstances.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Resilience is defined as positive adaptation DESPITE adversity — absence of adversity doesn't demonstrate it.\n(C) SES contributes but isn't sufficient — children can lack resilience without supportive relationships.\n(D) Genetics contribute to temperamental resilience but aren't the sole or primary predictor."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The Strange Situation (Ainsworth) assesses:", options:["General cognitive developmental milestones using standardized Piagetian conservation tasks","Infant-caregiver attachment quality through structured separation and reunion observation","Exclusively inborn temperamental characteristics independent of any relational caregiver factors","Intellectual quotient potential as measured by standardized infant cognitive assessment batteries"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) The Strange Situation is a structured observational procedure assessing attachment through observed reactions to separations from and reunions with the caregiver, plus behavior with a stranger.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Cognitive development is assessed by Piagetian tasks, Bayley Scales, etc.\n(C) While temperament influences behavior, the procedure measures the attachment RELATIONSHIP.\n(D) IQ potential is assessed by cognitive intelligence tests, not attachment procedures."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Permissive parenting (Baumrind) is characterized by:", options:["High parental warmth combined with low behavioral control, few rules, and minimal expectations","Low parental warmth combined with high behavioral control and strict authoritarian enforcement","Low parental warmth combined with low behavioral control reflecting neglectful uninvolvement","High parental warmth combined with high behavioral control reflecting authoritative balanced parenting"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (A) Permissive (indulgent) parents are warm, accepting, and responsive but make few demands, set few limits, and avoid confrontation. Children tend to be impulsive, lack self-regulation, and have difficulty with authority.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(B) Low warmth, high control = authoritarian parenting.\n(C) Low warmth, low control = uninvolved/neglectful parenting.\n(D) High warmth, high control = authoritative parenting (the optimal style)."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Emerging adulthood (Arnett) spans approximately:", options:["Ages 10-15 corresponding to early adolescent pubertal developmental transition period","Ages 18-25 characterized by identity exploration, instability, self-focus, and possibilities","Ages 30-40 corresponding to the early middle adulthood career consolidation period","Ages 55-65 corresponding to late middle adulthood pre-retirement planning transition period"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Arnett proposed emerging adulthood (ages 18-25) as a distinct developmental period characterized by identity exploration, instability, self-focus, feeling in-between, and a sense of possibilities.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Ages 10-15 = early adolescence.\n(C) Ages 30-40 = early middle adulthood.\n(D) Ages 55-65 = late middle adulthood approaching retirement."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Object permanence is fully achieved by approximately:", options:["4 months when infants begin tracking moving objects but don't yet search for hidden ones","8 months when partial object permanence emerges but A-not-B errors still commonly occur","18-24 months when invisible displacement understanding completes the sensorimotor achievement","Age 5 when preoperational thought enables symbolic representation of absent physical objects"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (C) Object permanence develops throughout the sensorimotor stage. Full object permanence (including invisible displacements — Stage 6) is achieved around 18-24 months. Partial object permanence begins around 8 months.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) At 4 months, infants don't yet search for hidden objects.\n(B) At 8 months, the A-not-B error shows incomplete object permanence.\n(D) By age 5, object permanence is long established — it's a sensorimotor achievement."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The 'personal fable' (Elkind) refers to adolescents' belief that:", options:["They are completely ordinary and unremarkable compared to every other person around them","Their experiences and feelings are unique, special, and incomprehensible to anyone else","They have absolutely no audience observing or paying attention to their behavior at all","They are fundamentally invulnerable to all natural laws including physical mortality risks"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) The personal fable: adolescents believe their experiences are unique, special, and unlike anyone else's ('No one understands me'). Related to feelings of invulnerability ('It won't happen to ME').\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The personal fable is about feeling EXTRAORDINARY, not ordinary.\n(C) Having no audience is the opposite of the imaginary audience concept (Elkind).\n(D) Invulnerability is a component of the personal fable but the fable is broader."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Parallel play is typical of children around age:", options:["6 months when infants primarily engage in solitary sensorimotor exploratory play activities","2-3 years when toddlers play alongside peers with similar materials but without direct interaction","6-7 years when children engage in cooperative rule-governed games with organized team structures","10-12 years when children participate in highly social organized competitive team sport activities"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Parallel play (Parten): children around 2-3 years play alongside other children with similar materials but without direct interaction or coordination. A transitional stage between solitary and cooperative play.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) At 6 months, infants engage in solitary/onlooker play, not parallel play.\n(C) By 6-7, children engage in cooperative and organized play.\n(D) By 10-12, play is highly social, rule-governed, and organized."},

        // ===== Domain 5: Assessment (10) =====
        {domainId:5, q:"The standard error of measurement (SEM) indicates:", options:["The arithmetic mean average test score across the entire normative standardization sample","The expected range of score fluctuation around a true score due to random measurement error","The degree to which a test measures what it purports to measure as a validity coefficient","The total number of participants included in the original normative standardization sample"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) SEM estimates how much an individual's observed score might vary from their true score due to random measurement error. A smaller SEM indicates more precise measurement. SEM = SD × √(1 - reliability).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Average test score = mean, a central tendency measure.\n(C) Validity refers to whether the test measures what it claims — SEM addresses measurement precision.\n(D) Normative sample size is a test development characteristic, not related to SEM."},
        {domainId:5, q:"A T-score of 70 on a clinical scale corresponds to:", options:["The mean of the T-score distribution which is set at 50 with a standard deviation of 10","One standard deviation above the mean which would correspond to a T-score of exactly 60","Two standard deviations above the mean which is often considered the clinical significance threshold","Three standard deviations above the mean which would correspond to a T-score of exactly 80"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (C) T-scores: M = 50, SD = 10. A T-score of 70 = 50 + 2(10) = 2 SDs above the mean. On the MMPI-2, T ≥ 65 is typically considered clinically significant.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The mean T-score = 50, not 70.\n(B) 1 SD above the mean = T-score of 60 (50 + 10).\n(D) 3 SDs above the mean = T-score of 80 (50 + 30)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Concurrent validity is established by:", options:["Administering a test on two occasions separated by time and correlating the resulting score pairs","Correlating test scores with a criterion measure obtained at the SAME time as the test administration","Using the test to predict future performance outcomes measured at a substantially later time point","Having content domain experts systematically review and evaluate the relevance of all test items"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Concurrent validity: the test score correlates with a criterion measure obtained at approximately the same time (e.g., correlating a new depression scale with the BDI-II administered simultaneously).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Administering twice and correlating = test-retest reliability.\n(C) Predicting future performance = predictive validity (criterion measures obtained LATER).\n(D) Expert review of items = content validity."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Rorschach Inkblot Test using the Exner Comprehensive System provides:", options:["Only subjective clinical impressions without any standardized scoring procedures or normative data","Standardized scoring procedures with normative data, established reliability, and valid clinical indices","A complete diagnosis based on a single inkblot response without need for full administration","Computer-generated personality profiles that require no clinical interpretation expertise at all"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Exner developed a standardized, empirically-based scoring system for the Rorschach with normative data, established reliability, and valid indices, moving it beyond purely clinical impression.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The Exner system specifically provides OBJECTIVE, standardized scoring.\n(C) Rorschach interpretation uses patterns across ALL responses, never a single response.\n(D) Computer scoring assists but interpretation requires clinical expertise."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Regression to the mean explains why:", options:["Extreme scores on initial testing tend to move toward the population average upon subsequent retesting","All scores remain perfectly stable and unchanged across repeated administrations without any variation","Test-retest reliability coefficients are always perfect at 1.0 indicating zero random measurement error","Normal distributions don't apply to psychological tests because scores are uniformly distributed"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (A) Regression to the mean: extreme scores (very high or very low) on initial testing tend to move toward the population mean on retesting. This is a statistical phenomenon, not necessarily reflecting real change.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(B) Scores fluctuate — they don't all remain perfectly stable.\n(C) No test has perfect reliability — measurement error always exists.\n(D) Normal distributions are widely used in psychological testing."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The PAI (Personality Assessment Inventory) differs from the MMPI-2 in that it:", options:["Has no validity scales and therefore cannot detect response style patterns or impression management","Uses a 4-point Likert response scale rather than the MMPI-2's dichotomous true/false format","Is designed only for children and adolescents and cannot be validly administered to adult populations","Cannot detect malingering or exaggeration of symptoms through any of its response validity indices"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) The PAI (Morey, 1991) uses a 4-point scale (false/slightly true/mainly true/very true) allowing gradation of response — unlike the MMPI-2's dichotomous true/false format. It has 344 items with 22 non-overlapping scales.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The PAI HAS validity scales (Inconsistency, Infrequency, Negative Impression, Positive Impression).\n(C) The PAI is designed for adults (age 18+), not exclusively for children.\n(D) The PAI can detect malingering through its validity indices (NIM, MAL, RDF)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Differential item functioning (DIF) analysis examines whether:", options:["Individual test items are simply too easy for all examinees regardless of their demographic characteristics","Test items function differently across demographic groups after controlling for overall ability levels","The overall test length is excessive and contributes to fatigue effects that diminish performance","The test's internal consistency reliability coefficient meets acceptable psychometric standards"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) DIF analysis identifies test items that function differently across groups (e.g., gender, ethnicity) AFTER controlling for overall ability level. Items with DIF may indicate bias and may need revision or removal.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Item difficulty is assessed by item difficulty indices (p-values), not DIF analysis.\n(C) Test length considerations relate to test design, not DIF.\n(D) Reliability adequacy is assessed by Cronbach's alpha, test-retest, etc."},
        {domainId:5, q:"In classical test theory, an observed score equals:", options:["Only the true score representing the examinee's actual ability without any error component","The true score plus the error score reflecting both ability and random measurement imprecision","The error score minus the true score producing a residual difference index of measurement quality","The standardized z-score transformation representing relative standing within a normative reference group"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) CTT formula: X (observed) = T (true) + E (error). Every observed score contains the person's true ability PLUS random measurement error. Reliability is the ratio of true score variance to observed score variance.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) If there were no error, all tests would have perfect reliability.\n(C) Error minus true score produces a meaningless value — CTT uses addition.\n(D) Standardized scores are transformations of observed scores, not the CTT formula."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Ecological validity of a neuropsychological assessment refers to:", options:["Whether the assessment was administered in an outdoor naturalistic environmental setting","Whether test performance accurately predicts real-world functional abilities and daily living skills","Whether the test exclusively uses naturalistic stimuli that closely resemble real-world objects","Whether the test was originally developed through a field study research methodology approach"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Ecological validity in neuropsychological assessment: whether test scores meaningfully predict a patient's ability to function in daily life (driving, managing finances, living independently).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The 'ecological' doesn't refer to outdoor environments — it refers to real-world applicability.\n(C) Natural stimuli may increase ecological validity but don't define it.\n(D) Field study development relates to research methodology, not clinical validity."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Ceiling effects in testing occur when:", options:["Test scores cluster at the bottom of the scale because the test is too difficult for examinees","The test is too easy causing scores to cluster at the top with little differentiation among high-ability examinees","The test contains an excessive number of items that creates fatigue and response inconsistency patterns","The test's reliability coefficient is too low to produce consistent scores across repeated administrations"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Ceiling effects: when a test is too easy, most examinees score near the maximum, preventing differentiation among high-ability individuals.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Scores clustering at the bottom = floor effect (the opposite).\n(C) Too many items is a test design issue but doesn't specifically cause ceiling effects.\n(D) Low reliability is a separate psychometric concern from ceiling effects."},

        // ===== Domain 6: Treatment (10) =====
        {domainId:6, q:"Exposure and response prevention (ERP) is the gold-standard treatment for:", options:["Schizophrenia spectrum disorders requiring antipsychotic pharmacotherapy and psychosocial rehabilitation","Obsessive-compulsive disorder through systematic exposure to triggers while preventing compulsive rituals","Bipolar disorder requiring mood stabilizer pharmacotherapy combined with structured psychotherapy approaches","Intellectual disability requiring behavioral skill-building interventions and supported living arrangements"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) ERP for OCD: the patient is exposed to obsession-triggering stimuli (exposure) while refraining from compulsive rituals (response prevention). This allows habituation and disconfirmation of feared outcomes.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Schizophrenia → antipsychotics + psychosocial rehabilitation.\n(C) Bipolar disorder → mood stabilizers (lithium, valproate) + psychotherapy.\n(D) Intellectual disability → behavioral interventions, supported living, not ERP."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The therapeutic alliance is BEST defined as:", options:["The therapist's specific theoretical orientation and preferred treatment modality or clinical framework","The collaborative relationship between therapist and client characterized by bond, goals, and task agreement","The client's perfect compliance with all assigned between-session homework exercises and activities","Insurance company preauthorization and administrative approval required before initiating treatment services"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Bordin's working alliance model: three components — bond (mutual trust, liking, respect), goals (agreement on treatment goals), and tasks (agreement on therapeutic activities). Strongest predictor of therapy outcomes.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Theoretical orientation is the therapist's framework — the alliance is the RELATIONSHIP quality.\n(C) Homework compliance may reflect the alliance but doesn't define it.\n(D) Insurance authorization is an administrative matter, not a therapeutic relationship concept."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Prolonged exposure therapy (Foa) for PTSD involves:", options:["Systematically avoiding all trauma reminders to prevent retraumatization and emotional destabilization","Repeated systematic revisiting of trauma memories through imaginal and in vivo exposure techniques","Only progressive muscle relaxation training without any direct confrontation of traumatic material","Exclusively psychopharmacological medication management without any psychotherapeutic interventions at all"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Foa's PE: imaginal exposure (recounting the trauma narrative repeatedly until habituation occurs) + in vivo exposure (gradually approaching avoided trauma-related situations). Emotional processing theory underlies the approach.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Avoidance MAINTAINS PTSD — PE specifically targets avoidance through exposure.\n(C) Relaxation is sometimes used as a coping tool but is NOT the active ingredient in PE.\n(D) PE is a psychotherapy — it may be combined with medication but isn't medication management."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The stages of change model (Prochaska & DiClemente) begins with:", options:["The action stage where the individual is already actively making concrete observable behavioral changes","The contemplation stage where the individual is ambivalently considering the possibility of change","The precontemplation stage where the individual is not yet considering any need for behavioral change","The maintenance stage where the individual is working to sustain previously accomplished behavioral changes"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (C) Stages: Precontemplation (not considering change) → Contemplation (ambivalent) → Preparation → Action → Maintenance. Understanding a client's stage guides intervention approach.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Action is stage 4 — the person is actively making changes.\n(B) Contemplation is stage 2 — the person is considering change but hasn't committed.\n(D) Maintenance is stage 5 — the person is sustaining changes already made."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Functional analysis in behavioral therapy identifies:", options:["Unconscious intrapsychic conflicts originating in early childhood developmental psychosexual stages","The antecedents, behaviors, and consequences (ABC) that maintain a specific problem behavior","Latent dream symbolism requiring psychoanalytic interpretation of manifest dream content material","Core maladaptive cognitive beliefs and automatic thoughts underlying negative emotional reactions"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Functional analysis (ABC model): identifies what triggers behavior (Antecedents), describes the specific Behavior, and examines what reinforces it (Consequences). This guides behavioral intervention design.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Unconscious conflicts = psychoanalytic focus, not behavioral analysis.\n(C) Dream symbolism = psychoanalytic technique (dream analysis).\n(D) Core beliefs = cognitive therapy (Beck), not functional behavioral analysis."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Interpersonal therapy (IPT) focuses on:", options:["Childhood unconscious intrapsychic conflicts rooted in unresolved psychosexual developmental stages","Current interpersonal difficulties in four problem areas: grief, role disputes, role transitions, and deficits","Identifying and disputing irrational beliefs through systematic logical analysis and empirical testing","Modifying behavioral contingencies through operant reinforcement schedules and stimulus control procedures"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) IPT (Klerman & Weissman): evidence-based, time-limited treatment for depression focusing on current interpersonal relationships in four domains — grief, role disputes, role transitions, and interpersonal deficits.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) IPT focuses on CURRENT relationships, not childhood unconscious material.\n(C) Irrational beliefs = REBT (Ellis) or cognitive therapy (Beck).\n(D) Behavioral contingencies = operant/behavioral treatment approaches."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Harm reduction approaches to substance use differ from abstinence-only by:", options:["Requiring immediate complete sobriety as an absolute precondition before any treatment can begin","Accepting that some substance use may occur while systematically working to minimize negative consequences","Actively encouraging increased substance use as a therapeutic paradoxical intervention strategy approach","Completely ignoring substance use entirely and focusing exclusively on unrelated mental health concerns"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Harm reduction: pragmatic, non-judgmental approach that reduces dangerous consequences of substance use without requiring abstinence as a precondition. Examples: needle exchanges, methadone maintenance, controlled drinking.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Harm reduction specifically does NOT require immediate sobriety — that's the abstinence-only approach.\n(C) Harm reduction aims to REDUCE harm, not increase use.\n(D) Harm reduction actively addresses substance use — it just doesn't require abstinence as the only goal."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Narrative therapy (White & Epston) involves helping clients:", options:["Only focusing intensively on problems while analyzing their root causes and maintaining factors","Externalize problems and re-author their life stories using preferred alternative narrative identities","Follow strict manualized behavioral protocols with predetermined session-by-session treatment structure","Analyze unconscious motivations through free association and transference interpretation techniques"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Narrative therapy: problems are externalized ('the problem is the problem, not the person'), and clients re-author their narratives by identifying 'unique outcomes' — exceptions to the problem story that support a preferred identity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Narrative therapy actively moves AWAY from problem-saturated stories toward alternative narratives.\n(C) It's a collaborative, non-prescriptive approach — not strict behavioral protocols.\n(D) Unconscious analysis = psychoanalytic approach, not narrative therapy."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Lithium is the first-line pharmacological treatment for:", options:["Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder treated primarily with psychostimulant or non-stimulant medications","Major depressive disorder treated primarily with selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor antidepressants","Bipolar I disorder requiring mood stabilization for acute mania, maintenance, and suicide prevention","Generalized anxiety disorder treated primarily with SSRIs, SNRIs, or buspirone anxiolytic medications"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (C) Lithium is the gold-standard mood stabilizer for bipolar disorder — effective for acute mania, maintenance, and suicide prevention. Requires blood level monitoring due to narrow therapeutic index.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) ADHD → stimulants (methylphenidate, amphetamine) or non-stimulants (atomoxetine).\n(B) MDD first-line → SSRIs or SNRIs, not lithium (though lithium can augment antidepressants).\n(D) GAD → SSRIs/SNRIs, buspirone, or benzodiazepines (short-term), not lithium."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The Dodo bird verdict in psychotherapy research refers to:", options:["A specific empirically validated therapeutic technique used exclusively in psychodynamic treatment approaches","The finding that different bona fide psychotherapies tend to produce roughly equivalent treatment outcomes","The established superiority of one specific psychotherapy modality demonstrated over all other approaches","The finding that all psychotherapies are completely ineffective and produce no meaningful clinical change"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Named from Alice in Wonderland ('Everyone has won, all must have prizes'): meta-analyses show that different legitimate psychotherapies produce roughly equivalent outcomes, supporting the common factors model over specific technique models.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's a research FINDING about therapy outcomes, not a specific technique.\n(C) The Dodo bird verdict specifically argues AGAINST the superiority of any single therapy.\n(D) Therapies ARE effective — the verdict is about EQUIVALENCE of outcomes, not ineffectiveness."},

        // ===== Domain 7: Research Methods (10) =====
        {domainId:7, q:"A Type I error occurs when:", options:["The researcher fails to reject a false null hypothesis resulting in a false negative conclusion","The researcher incorrectly rejects a true null hypothesis resulting in a false positive conclusion","The study has insufficient statistical power due to an inadequately small sample size recruited","The study sample is excessively large producing trivially small but statistically significant effects"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Type I error (α error/false positive): concluding an effect exists when it doesn't — rejecting H₀ when H₀ is actually true. Controlled by setting alpha level (typically .05).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Failing to reject a false null = Type II error (β error/false negative).\n(C) Low power increases Type II errors, not Type I errors.\n(D) Large samples can produce trivially significant effects but this isn't a Type I error per se."},
        {domainId:7, q:"External validity is MOST threatened by:", options:["Random assignment procedures that equalize participant characteristics across experimental conditions","Non-representative sampling methods and highly artificial laboratory testing conditions","Large and diverse sample sizes that broadly represent the target population of interest","Use of appropriate control groups that provide meaningful comparison baselines for effects"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) External validity (generalizability) is reduced when samples don't represent the target population or when laboratory conditions don't match real-world settings.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Random assignment enhances INTERNAL validity, not threats to external validity.\n(C) Large samples generally IMPROVE external validity through broader representation.\n(D) Control groups enhance internal validity without threatening external validity."},
        {domainId:7, q:"A mediator variable explains:", options:["When or for whom a particular effect occurs by specifying boundary conditions and interactions","HOW or WHY an independent variable produces its effect on the dependent variable mechanistically","That two variables under investigation are completely unrelated and share no common variance","Only random unsystematic measurement error variance that obscures true relationships between variables"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Mediator: the mechanism through which X affects Y. X → M → Y. Example: Exercise (X) → improved mood (M) → reduced depression (Y). Mediators explain the causal pathway.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) When/for whom an effect occurs = moderator variable (interaction effect).\n(C) A mediator specifically establishes a RELATIONSHIP pathway between variables.\n(D) Mediators explain systematic variance, not random error."},
        {domainId:7, q:"A moderator variable specifies:", options:["The underlying causal mechanism through which an independent variable produces its observed effect","Under WHAT CONDITIONS or FOR WHOM the relationship between two variables changes in direction or strength","That the independent variable definitively and directly causes changes in the dependent variable","That the dependent variable actually causes changes in the independent variable through reverse causation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Moderator: a variable that changes the STRENGTH or DIRECTION of the relationship between X and Y. Example: Age moderates the relationship between stress and health (effect is stronger for older adults).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Mechanism = mediator; moderators specify WHEN, not HOW.\n(C) Moderators don't establish causation — they specify boundary conditions.\n(D) Moderators don't indicate reverse causation."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Effect size measures:", options:["Only statistical significance as determined by the p-value relative to the chosen alpha level","The magnitude and practical importance of a finding independent of sample size considerations","The minimum required sample size needed to achieve adequate statistical power for detection","Whether the null hypothesis is definitively true or false in the target population of interest"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Effect size quantifies the magnitude of an effect (Cohen's d, η², r²), conveying practical significance independent of sample size. A finding can be statistically significant but have a trivial effect size.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Statistical significance (p-value) is separate from effect size — they answer different questions.\n(C) Sample size requirements are determined through power analysis, which USES effect size as an input.\n(D) Effect sizes quantify the magnitude of an effect — they don't prove or disprove null hypotheses."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Intention-to-treat analysis includes:", options:["Only participants who successfully completed the entire study protocol without any protocol deviations","ALL participants originally randomized regardless of whether they completed or complied with treatment","Only participants who demonstrated measurable clinical improvement during the course of the study","Only participants assigned to the control group excluding all participants in active treatment conditions"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) ITT analysis includes ALL randomized participants in their original groups, even if they dropped out, didn't comply, or switched groups. This preserves the benefits of randomization and provides a more realistic effectiveness estimate.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Including only completers = per-protocol analysis, which can introduce attrition bias.\n(C) Including only improvers = extreme bias violating the purpose of the trial.\n(D) ITT includes ALL groups, not just the control."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Ceiling and floor effects reduce:", options:["Only the reliability of the test without affecting any other psychometric properties or statistical analyses","The ability to detect true differences by restricting variability and attenuating statistical power","The minimum sample size required to achieve adequate statistical power for detecting meaningful effects","The necessity for including appropriate control groups in experimental and quasi-experimental research designs"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Ceiling/floor effects restrict score variability — if everyone scores at the top or bottom, the measure can't differentiate among individuals, reducing the ability to detect true differences (attenuated correlations, reduced power).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They affect both reliability AND the ability to detect differences — not only reliability.\n(C) They don't reduce sample size needs — if anything, they require LARGER samples to detect effects.\n(D) They have no relationship to the need for control groups."},
        {domainId:7, q:"A quasi-experimental design differs from a true experiment primarily because it:", options:["Has no formal research hypothesis being tested about relationships between independent and dependent variables","Lacks random assignment of participants to experimental and control conditions before manipulation","Has no measurable dependent variable being systematically observed and recorded by the researchers","Uses only qualitative interview data rather than any form of quantitative numerical measurement data"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Quasi-experiments have an IV manipulation but lack random assignment. Participants are in pre-existing groups (classrooms, hospitals, gender). This limits causal inference due to potential confounds.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Quasi-experiments DO have hypotheses — they test them without full experimental control.\n(C) Quasi-experiments measure dependent variables — they're structured like experiments.\n(D) Quasi-experiments can use quantitative data — the only difference is random assignment."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Publication bias occurs when:", options:["All research studies are published equally regardless of their statistical outcomes or effect sizes","Studies with statistically significant results are preferentially published over those with null findings","Only qualitative phenomenological research studies are accepted for publication in academic journals","Researchers simply publish an excessive volume of studies without regard to methodological quality"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Publication bias (file drawer problem): journals preferentially publish significant findings. Studies with null results go unpublished, creating a distorted literature that overestimates effect sizes.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Equal publication is the IDEAL — publication bias is the systematic departure from this.\n(C) Both quantitative and qualitative studies face publication pressures.\n(D) The bias is about SELECTIVE publication based on results, not volume of publications."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Cohen's kappa measures:", options:["Effect size indicating the magnitude of a treatment outcome or group difference in a study","Inter-rater agreement for categorical judgments corrected for the probability of chance agreement","Test-retest temporal stability reliability assessed by correlating scores from two administration occasions","Internal consistency reliability assessed through Cronbach's alpha or split-half correlation methodologies"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Cohen's κ measures agreement between two raters for categorical judgments, correcting for the probability of chance agreement. κ = 1.0 = perfect agreement; κ = 0 = chance-level agreement.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Effect size measures (Cohen's d, η²) quantify magnitude of findings, not inter-rater agreement.\n(C) Test-retest reliability = correlating scores from two administrations over time.\n(D) Internal consistency = Cronbach's alpha or split-half reliability, measuring item intercorrelation."}
    ];

    batch14.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch14.length} additional questions (batch 14 — enhanced rationales).`);
})();
